From f8fd884a9df2e88f2237e25b51329d98fef93106 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Sangwook Han <sangwook.han@gmail.com>
Date: Sat, 6 Jun 2026 11:50:42 +0900
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] Extract the pure timer state machine into a PTimerCore
 package (step 1/2)

What: move the platform-neutral timer logic out of the app's
TimerManager.swift into a new `PTimerKit` package (`PTimerCore` target):
- TimerState sum type + RunningTimer/PausedTimer/CompletedTimer and the
  pause/resume/complete/remaining-time transitions
- PersistentTimerSnapshot/collection + persistence store protocol & impls
- CompletedRelativeTimeFormatter
TimerManager stays in the app target as the OS coordinator (RunLoop
ticking, UIKit feedback, UserNotifications, ActivityKit, @Published,
persistence wiring) and now depends on PTimerCore.

Why: TimerManager conflated the pure timer rules with UIKit/notification
I/O, so timer behavior could not be reasoned about or tested in
isolation. Separating the pure core is a standalone structural
improvement; it also unblocks running timer-dependent tests without the
simulator (step 2). The stability epsilon is mirrored as a local
constant so the core has no dependency on the exposure engine.

Behavior preserved: full app suite stays green (1474 tests, 0 failures);
the PTimerCore package builds with `swift test`.

Step 2/2 will relocate the pure timer-core tests into PTimerCoreTests so
they run on macOS without a simulator.

PTIMER-177 Decouple the pure timer state machine from the UIKit-bound
           TimerManager

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
